metadata.name: Lost Memories #12
metadata.description:
||_\\_//_\\_||

Let‚Äôs start with a riddle‚Ä¶
I‚Äôm a type of creature that never tires.
My desire to learn is truly inspired.
I‚Äôd back expanding to the letter.
As more of everything is better.
I could not stop though the world is sick.
And now my only memories are apocalyptic. 
What am I?

If you‚Äôd like to know a bit about the ideas behind this piece, and my method for a code based paint effect, see the fxtext article ‚ÄúLost Memories - Painting like an impressionist android‚Äù. Link at the bottom. However feel free to skip the article, my meaning, and everything else if so desired.

||_\\_//_\\_||

Basic info:
This piece uses web tech and WebGL in experimental ways to achieve the paint-like effect. This includes a custom built drawing pipeline. Although well tested, please be sure it's fine for your devices before buying ( give it a whirl drawing basically ). 

A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that‚Äôs present.

The piece comes in portrait to make use of the depth of the body of water. The ratio is 1.5. So the initial render will be 1000px wide and 1500px high. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

||_\\_//_\\_||

Saving the image / prints
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. You will know when the render is finished as there will be 3 layers of fish made. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right-click save otherwise.

Correct sizing for HD digital images / laptops / phones
Use the [s] key (see above), at most use the [2] key ( see below ) to get double the size. Honestly, anything larger and you will begin to lose the textures as the detail becomes too fine. 

Correct sizing for large prints
I strongly suggest using the [3] key ( see below - 3000 x 4500 pixels ) for large prints. I‚Äôve tested this on a 20x30 inch print and it‚Äôs the best size. Anything bigger will begin to lose texture and lose detail. However, the option for bigger is there. 

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x3000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x13500 size image etc ( see above for correct sizing ). After the image will be automatically downloaded.

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however.

||_\\_//_\\_||

Made with javascript (webgl) and some small extra code:
Some bits by @nathansonic
Twgl - A webgl wrapper -  twgljs.org
A Perlin noise generator - github.com/josephg/noisejs

metadata.name: Arcadia #6 #18
metadata.description:
Space city! üöÄüëΩüõ∞ü™êüë©üèº‚ÄçüöÄ‚òÑÔ∏è

Arcadia is a project where we work on the basis of a 3D world created from voxels with a 2D isometric rendering. The engine has been built using the p5.js library as the basis for many iterations of the project.

Arcadia goes up to space in this edition. Creating a spatial atmosphere by playing with light and shadow on a starry background, an attempt has been made to simulate a city floating in space. I have explored the manipulation of color ranges through perlin noise to create lighting effects.

After the generation of the world is finished, the city is named with the IBM VGA font to add a retro touch.

Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about ‚ÄúBreeding Grounds‚Äù and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

metadata.description:
Angles represent the artist's view of the space and the visible subject, and the position is chosen so that the audience is able to see the subject from that angle.
The angles determine the audience's point of view in this way and by changing the angles, the audience can see the subject of the image from a new perspective.

metadata.name: CMYK:Unchecked #77
metadata.description:
CMYK:Unchecked offers almost infinite canvases designed to challenge the concept and state of being unverified.

Layout variations include 80 / 40 / 20 / 10 / 5 / 4 / 1 circles. 
Each circle presented is either Cyan, Magento, Yellow or Black.

---

This work is of course a parody of 'Checks' by Jack Butcher presented in a transformative way. The work is in no way related to the original 'Checks' work and is not intended to fool anyone into thinking so thus does not affect the originals market or value.

metadata.name: Snow Mountains #26
metadata.description:
"Snow Mountains"

Since my first trek in India in 2013 (Stok Kangri - 6137m), I have always been fascinated by these gigantic boulders.

They remind us how small we are facing nature.

With this collection (created with p5js), I have given them back their power.

Here are the variables used:
- Each point is calculated randomly creating random shapes
- A mountain chosen randomly among the 425 highest.
- A color palette chosen randomly from the 100 proposed.

By clicking on the image, you can save it in .jpeg format.

These mountains will enhance your NFT collection.

metadata.name: Forgive Your Sins #56
metadata.description:
This is a colorful remix for #genuary32nd of my late #genuary23 work done on 31st of January!
This is my tribute to Yayoi Kusama (#genuary25) with viscous dots of digital ink thrown in digital liquid and then shaken by digital sine waves (#genuary15) inspired by marbling techniques.

This is the 2nd iteration of my Wasm/Rust fluid simulation engine after "Viscous Circles" collection. Check it on FxHash if you want to know more about the engine behind this generator.

Controls

You can stop at any step if you like the state at this instant, you can restart it, de/increase resolution (default is 4096x4096 to have sharp image, up to 16K x 16K) and snapshot at any resolution.

- H: hide/show help.
- Space - pause/start animation.
- R - restart animation.
- I - hide/show res/fps panel.
- A-Q/D - down/up full resolution
- S - take full resolution snapshot

Now, forgive your sins!

Forgive Your Sins @naibdian 2023 Project made using Opensource WebGL, WASM/Rust/JS libs
#genuary32nd #genuary23 #genuary15 #genuary25

metadata.name: No Writing on Walls #5
metadata.description:
"No Writing on Walls," is a visual representation of the concept of writing on walls as a form of self-expression. The abstract wall covered in graffiti and positive words serves to showcase the diverse voices and messages that people want to share, despite the restriction against writing on walls. My aim was to challenge the negative stereotypes associated with graffiti and demonstrate the beauty and creativity that can arise when people are allowed to express themselves freely. With this artwork, I hope to spark reflection and encourage viewers to consider the power of self-expression and its impact on individuals and society.
- Look for the gold mode
- press p so export png
- press s to export svg

metadata.name: Iteration is Usually Recursive (Pt. 1) #55
metadata.description:
This is the companion piece released with 'Iteration is Usually Recursive ‚Äî Introduction: Finding answers in pre-computational art', the first in a series of essays, some long, some short, on generative art, theory and the practitioners of the medium. 

This piece started a simple experimen recreating George Nees‚Äô Schotter (1968)‚Äî a classic piece of generative art history ‚Äî as vanilla js SVG graphics. From there, I specifically developed it with non-plotter printing in mind, and more specific still, Riso Printing (think a scanner with a digital screen-printer MacGyver‚Äôd on). The palettes are taken from hex-estimated Risograph colour gamuts, with three layers being multiplied together to replicate, to some degree, the blending of the semi-transparent Risographic inks. Within this study, there‚Äôs a few different things going on, the initial setup is rectangles which cascade down the canvas, inheriting more extreme rotation as they get closer to the bottom (a la Schotter). The second is a subdivision of the shapes with filled circled, outlined circles and squares ‚Äî since in this study the base shapes are rectangles and not squares, distribution of the ‚Äòdithering‚Äô can be larger than a single ‚Äòpixel‚Äô size ‚Äî when these multiple layers overlap, the shapes produce a halftone-moire effect, forms and structures appear from the noise as the underlying patterns intersect. 

tx: Who?, Cosimo, Liam Egan, Andreas Rau, Louis
